name: 4-fluoro-3-methylbenzeneboronic acid
Reason: To predict the melting point of 4-fluoro-3-methylbenzeneboronic acid, we need to analyze the influence of each functional group compared to benzene. The basic benzene structure has a known melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. The methyl group typically increases the melting point due to increased molecular weight and greater van der Waals interactions, contributing around +20 degrees. Fluorine, being an electronegative substituent, influences the aromatic system, creating more dipole interactions and increasing the melting point by approximately +40 degrees due to its inductive effect and the increase in molecular rigidity. The boronic acid group forms intermolecular hydrogen bonds, which significantly elevates the melting point. Hydrogen bonding is a significant factor and can contribute upward of +120 degrees, considering the strength of B-O interactions in concert with the acidity of the boronic acid moiety. Cumulatively, these additions sum to predict the melting point.
Prediction: Benzene base: 5.5 + Methyl: +20 + Fluorine: +40 + Boronic acid: +120 = 5.5 + 20 + 40 + 120 = 185.5 degrees Celsius
